Recommended size for TaskyHub
For a single-tenant test/staging TaskyHub (Postgres + API + AE + Grafana + UI) on one EC2 instance:

vCPU: 2 vCPUs minimum, 4 vCPUs is more comfortable if you use Grafana and AE heavily.

RAM: 4 GB minimum, 8 GB if you want smooth performance and headroom.

Disk:

Root/EBS: 50–100 GB gp3 or gp2, with at least baseline 3000 IOPS (default for gp3 is fine for this scale).

Concrete AWS suggestions (for testing / light production):

Minimum workable: t3.small (2 vCPU, 2 GB RAM) with 50–100 GB gp3.

Better and still cheap: t3.medium (2 vCPU, 4 GB RAM) with 50–100 GB gp3.

Very comfortable: t3.large (2 vCPU, 8 GB RAM) or t3a.large for cost savings.

Given your workload (Postgres + Node + Grafana, possibly AE later), I’d pick:

Instance type: t3.medium

Disk: 80 GB gp3, default IOPS

That will:

Eliminate the >80% disk utilization you’re seeing now.

Give enough RAM that Postgres and Node are not constantly fighting the kernel for memory.

If this is just dev/testing and you want to minimize cost, t3.small (2 GB) can work but you must:

Avoid running heavy Grafana dashboards.

Keep AE / other services minimal.

Right now, your 1 GB box is below that minimum, which is why you see high %wa, full memory, and slow Docker responses.